== The Murakuni Clan in Mino Province == The Murakuni Clan was based in {{ill|Mino Province|ja|美濃国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mino Province|qq=}}’s {{ill|Kagami District|ja|各務郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagami District|qq=}}, and there is a theory that they were a branch of the family of the {{ill|Owari Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|尾張国造|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}} ({{ill|Owari Ren|ja|尾張連|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Ren|qq=}}). Little is directly known about the Murakuni Clan prior to Otokoroe, and on a national scale they seem to have been an almost obscure minor local clan.
In the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}} work ''{{ill|Wamyō Ruijushō|ja|和名類聚抄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wamyō Ruijushō|qq=}}'', Murakuni communities (郷) are recorded in three locations: in {{ill|Kagami District, Mino Province|ja|美濃国各務郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagami District, Mino Province|qq=}}, in {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Province|qq=}}’s {{ill|Haguri District|ja|葉栗郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haguri District|qq=}}, and in {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|大和国|qq=Yamato Province|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Province|qq=}}’s {{ill|Soge District|ja|添下郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Soge District|qq=}}. It is speculated that the Murakuni-gō in Mino and Owari, which are separated only by the {{ill|Kiso River|ja|木曽川|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiso River|qq=}}, originally referred to the same area. The Heian-era "Engishiki Jinmyōchō" records that there are two Murakuni Shrines ({{ill|Murakuni Shrine|ja|村国神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shrine|qq=}}) and one {{ill|Murakuni Mamusuda Shrine|ja|村国真墨田神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Mamusuda Shrine|qq=}} in Kagami District. In Haguri District, although no Murakuni Shrine appears in the ''Engishiki'', there is another shrine bearing the name, and the temple {{ill|Ongaku-ji (Konan)|ja|音楽寺 (江南市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ongaku-ji (Konan)|qq=}} carries the tradition of having been built by Murakuni Otokoroe.
Furthermore, as noted later, Otokoroe and his grandson, {{ill|Murakuni Shimasu|ja|村国島主|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shimasu|qq=}}, had connections with Mino. In the 2nd year of the {{ill|Daihō era|ja|大宝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daihō era|qq=}} ({{ill|702|ja|702年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/702|qq=}}), a woman named Murakuni Okuren Kobiryū (奥連小竜女) appears in the family registers of the 【御野国山方郡三井田】. The ''{{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shoku Nihongi|qq=}}'' records that in the 4th year of the {{ill|Keiun era|ja|慶雲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keiun era|qq=}} ({{ill|707|ja|707年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/707|qq=}}) on May 16, a certain Murakuni Rento-shimē (村国連等志売) of Mino Province bore triplets. In this way, matters and persons associated with the Murakuni Clan are concentrated in Mino Province, lending strong support to the theory linking the Murakuni Clan with Kagami District, Mino.
The ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}'' attributes the surname {{ill|Ren|ja|連|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ren|qq=}} to Murakuni Otokoroe at the time of the Jinshin War, and subsequent historical texts consistently record the Murakuni Clan under the Ren surname. However, the Ren surname in the era of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|qq=}}—in the period immediately before and after the establishment of the "Eight Colors of Surnames" ({{ill|Yashoku no Uji|ja|八色の姓|1=Eight Kabane system|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yashoku no Uji|13=User:Immanuelle/Eight Kabane system|qq=}})—differed greatly in status, and the Ren surname at the time of the Jinshin War would have been too exalted for a minor local clan. An article in the 1st year of the {{ill|Daihō era|ja|大宝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daihō era|qq=}} ({{ill|701|ja|701st year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/701|qq=}}) in July, which lists heroes of the Jinshin War along with their surnames, records Murakuni Otokoroe (referred to as Murakuni Koyori (小依)) without any surname. If this is given due weight, it suggests that the clan did not originally possess a surname at the time of the Jinshin War, and that the Ren surname was conferred upon them afterward.
== The Murakuni Clan in the Imperial Court == The Murakuni Clan is introduced in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}'' through Murakuni Otokoroe, who served {{ill|Prince Ōama (later Emperor Tenmu)|ja|大海人皇子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Ōama (later Emperor Tenmu)|qq=}} ({{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|qq=}}). In the year of the Jinshin War ({{ill|672|ja|672年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/672|qq=}}), in June, Otokoroe was dispatched as an envoy to Mino Province to deliver Prince Ōama's order to raise an army—likely a consideration of his Mino origins. In July, he served as a central commander of the forces in the Omi region, which became the main theater of operations. Following the Jinshin War, Otokoroe was granted a fudo (封戸). After his death, he was awarded the Rank of external {{ill|Koshiki|ja|小紫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koshiki|qq=}}, and his son, {{ill|Murakuni Shigamaro|ja|村国志我麻呂|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shigamaro|qq=}}, was granted a honor known as {{ill|Kōden|ja|功田|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōden|qq=}}. Although these honors may seem modest compared to those given to the greatest achievers, they were significant rewards for someone originating from a local magnate.
In the first half of the 8th century, the Murakuni Clan attained mid- to lower-level noble status; Shigamaro reached the Rank of {{ill|Ju-go-i Jō|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ju-go-i Jō|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}}, while {{ill|Murakuni Komushi|ja|村国子虫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Komushi|qq=}} attained the Rank of external {{ill|Ju-go-i Ge|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ju-go-i Ge|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}}, barely reaching the 5th Rank despite his external status.
At the height of {{ill|Fujiwara no Nakamaro|ja|藤原仲麻呂|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Nakamaro|qq=}}’s power, Otokoroe’s grandson, {{ill|Murakuni Shimasu|ja|村国島主|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shimasu|qq=}}, initially entered Nakamaro’s service, and the clan enjoyed his patronage. Just before the {{ill|Fujiwara no Nakamaro Rebellion|ja|藤原仲麻呂の乱|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Nakamaro Rebellion|qq=}} in the 8th year of the {{ill|Tenpyō-hōji era|ja|天平宝字|1=Tenpyō-hōji|2=ja|3=天平宝字|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpyō-hōji era|qq=}} ({{ill|764|ja|764年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/764|qq=}}), Shimasu held the position of {{ill|Shōyaku|ja|少掾|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōyaku|qq=}} in Mino, {{ill|Murakuni Koro|ja|村国子老|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Koro|qq=}} served as the governor ({{ill|Kokushi|ja|国司|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi|qq=}}) of {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Province|qq=}}, and {{ill|Murakuni Mushi-maro|ja|村国虫麻呂|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Mushi-maro|qq=}} held the post of secretary ({{ill|Kaisei|ja|介|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaisei|qq=}}) in {{ill|Echizen Province|ja|越前国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echizen Province|qq=}}. This distribution of posts appears to have been part of Nakamaro’s plan to mobilize military forces from eastern and northern regions centered on {{ill|Omi Province|ja|近江国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Omi Province|qq=}}, but his failure to raise an army and subsequent defeat meant that the plan never came to fruition. Shimasu was killed by an envoy sent to secure the fortification at {{ill|Fuwa Barrier|ja|不破関|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fuwa Barrier|qq=}}, and the other two lost their gubernatorial appointments. Later, the Imperial Court exonerated Murakuni Shimasu. Although Koro and Mushi-maro, who had once fallen from power, later returned to serve at the same Rank as before, their descendants were unable to maintain their status.
Much later, a woman named {{ill|Murakuni Kazuko|ja|村国数子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Kazuko|qq=}}, who worked in the Imperial harem, reached the Rank of external {{ill|Ju-go-i Ge|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ju-go-i Ge|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}} in the 17th year of the {{ill|Jōgan|ja|貞観|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōgan|qq=}} era ({{ill|875|ja|875年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/875|qq=}}); she was the last member of the Murakuni Clan to attain the 5th Rank. Subsequently, the names of {{ill|Murakuni Gyōse|ja|村国業世|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Gyōse|qq=}} (of the upper {{ill|Shōroku|ja|正六位|1=Senior Sixth Rank|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōroku|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Sixth Rank|qq=}}) and his son {{ill|Murakuni Harusawa|ja|村国春沢|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Harusawa|qq=}} appear in the "Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku" in the 4th clause of the 1st year of the {{ill|Ninwa|ja|仁和|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninwa|qq=}} era ({{ill|885|ja|885年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/885|qq=}}).
