[[ja:%E6%9D%91%E5%9B%BD%E6%B0%8F]] [[sn:Murakuni Clan]] [[en:Murakuni Clan]] [[Category:中部地方の氏族]] [[Category:村国氏]] [[Category:氏]] [[Category:美濃国の氏族]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[ja:村国氏]]

'''Murakuni Clan''' ({{ill|Murakuni Clan|ja|村国氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Clan|qq=}}, Murakuni-ji) is a family that flourished as regional magnates and central officials in [[:en:Japan|Japan]] from the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]] to the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]]. Their hereditary title ([[:en:Kabane|Kabane]]) is [[:en:Muraji|Ren]]. Their stronghold was in [[:en:Mino Province|Mino Province]], {{ill|Kagami District|ja|各務郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagami District|qq=}}, and after [[:en:Murakuni Oyori|Murakuni Otokoroe]] distinguished himself during the [[:en:Jinshin War|Jinshin War]] in [[:en:672|672]], they went on to produce mid-level officials. In the 760s they were patronized by [[:en:Fujiwara no Nakamaro|Fujiwara no Nakamaro]], but this association led to their decline after the [[:en:Fujiwara no Nakamaro Rebellion|Fujiwara no Nakamaro Rebellion]] in [[:en:764|764]].
== The Murakuni Clan in Mino Province == The Murakuni Clan was based in [[:en:Mino Province|Mino Province]]’s {{ill|Kagami District|ja|各務郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagami District|qq=}}, and there is a theory that they were a branch of the family of the {{ill|Owari Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|尾張国造|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}} ({{ill|Owari Ren|ja|尾張連|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Ren|qq=}}). Little is directly known about the Murakuni Clan prior to Otokoroe, and on a national scale they seem to have been an almost obscure minor local clan.
In the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]] work ''[[:en:Wamyō Ruijushō|Wamyō Ruijushō]]'', Murakuni communities (郷) are recorded in three locations: in {{ill|Kagami District, Mino Province|ja|美濃国各務郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagami District, Mino Province|qq=}}, in [[:en:Owari Province|Owari Province]]’s [[:en:Haguri District|Haguri District]], and in [[:en:Yamato Province|Yamato Province]]’s {{ill|Soge District|ja|添下郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Soge District|qq=}}. It is speculated that the Murakuni-gō in Mino and Owari, which are separated only by the [[:en:Kiso River|Kiso River]], originally referred to the same area. The Heian-era "Engishiki Jinmyōchō" records that there are two Murakuni Shrines ({{ill|Murakuni Shrine|ja|村国神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shrine|qq=}}) and one {{ill|Murakuni Mamusuda Shrine|ja|村国真墨田神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Mamusuda Shrine|qq=}} in Kagami District. In Haguri District, although no Murakuni Shrine appears in the ''Engishiki'', there is another shrine bearing the name, and the temple {{ill|Ongaku-ji (Konan)|ja|音楽寺 (江南市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ongaku-ji (Konan)|qq=}} carries the tradition of having been built by Murakuni Otokoroe.
Furthermore, as noted later, Otokoroe and his grandson, {{ill|Murakuni Shimasu|ja|村国島主|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shimasu|qq=}}, had connections with Mino. In the 2nd year of the [[:en:Taiho|Daihō era]] ([[:en:702|702]]), a woman named Murakuni Okuren Kobiryū (奥連小竜女) appears in the family registers of the 【御野国山方郡三井田】. The ''[[:en:Shoku Nihongi|Shoku Nihongi]]'' records that in the 4th year of the [[:en:Keiun|Keiun era]] ([[:en:AD 707|707]]) on May 16, a certain Murakuni Rento-shimē (村国連等志売) of Mino Province bore triplets. In this way, matters and persons associated with the Murakuni Clan are concentrated in Mino Province, lending strong support to the theory linking the Murakuni Clan with Kagami District, Mino.
The ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' attributes the surname [[:en:Muraji|Ren]] to Murakuni Otokoroe at the time of the Jinshin War, and subsequent historical texts consistently record the Murakuni Clan under the Ren surname. However, the Ren surname in the era of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|qq=}}—in the period immediately before and after the establishment of the "Eight Colors of Surnames" ({{ill|Yashoku no Uji|ja|八色の姓|1=Eight Kabane system|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yashoku no Uji|13=User:Immanuelle/Eight Kabane system|qq=}})—differed greatly in status, and the Ren surname at the time of the Jinshin War would have been too exalted for a minor local clan. An article in the 1st year of the [[:en:Taiho|Daihō era]] ([[:en:701|701]]) in July, which lists heroes of the Jinshin War along with their surnames, records Murakuni Otokoroe (referred to as Murakuni Koyori (小依)) without any surname. If this is given due weight, it suggests that the clan did not originally possess a surname at the time of the Jinshin War, and that the Ren surname was conferred upon them afterward.
== The Murakuni Clan in the Imperial Court == The Murakuni Clan is introduced in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' through Murakuni Otokoroe, who served {{ill|Prince Ōama (later Emperor Tenmu)|ja|大海人皇子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Ōama (later Emperor Tenmu)|qq=}} ({{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|qq=}}). In the year of the Jinshin War ([[:en:672|672]]), in June, Otokoroe was dispatched as an envoy to Mino Province to deliver Prince Ōama's order to raise an army—likely a consideration of his Mino origins. In July, he served as a central commander of the forces in the Omi region, which became the main theater of operations. Following the Jinshin War, Otokoroe was granted a fudo (封戸). After his death, he was awarded the Rank of external {{ill|Koshiki|ja|小紫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koshiki|qq=}}, and his son, {{ill|Murakuni Shigamaro|ja|村国志我麻呂|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murakuni Shigamaro|qq=}}, was granted a honor known as {{ill|Kōden|ja|功田|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōden|qq=}}. Although these honors may seem modest compared to those given to the greatest achievers, they were significant rewards for someone originating from a local magnate.
